76–1420","1323–1361":"1323–1361","1320–Female":"1320–Deceased","about 1360":"about 1360","1330":"1330","1341":"1341","1362":"1362","1361":"1361","1370":"1370","1415":"1415","1358":"1358","1445":"1445","1323":"1323","1345":"1345","1344":"1344","1343":"1343","1420":"1420","1376":"1376","1365":"1365","1320":"1320","1375":"1375","Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Gwernyclepa, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Gwernyclepa, Monmouthshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]},{"name":"Ivor","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Scandinavian origin, from an Old Norse personal name, <i>Yherr</i>, derived from <i>ýr</i> ‘yew, bow’ + <i>herr</i> ‘army’. In the 1920s and 30s it came to prominence as the name of the songwriter and actor  Ivor Novello  (  1893–1951 )."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Hael","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Modern: from <i>haul</i> ‘sun’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas ap Ivor Hael was born in 1343, in Gwernyclepa, Monmouthshire, Wales, his father, Ivor Hael ap Llewelyn, was 21 and his mother, Nest verch Rhys, was 24. He had at least 1 son and 3 daughters with Jonet verch Llywelyn Fychan. He died in 1362, in Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom, at the age of 19."},"et":{"1343–1362":"1343–1362","